<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-lines" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Representations of Lines</title>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>
	Determine the slope of a line through two points.
      </li>
      <li>
	<p>
	  Represent a line using
	  <ul>
	    <li>Slope-Intercept Form,</li>
	    <li>Point-Slope Form, and</li>
	    <li>Standard Form.</li>
	  </ul>
	</p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <definition>
    <p>
      The <term>slope</term>
      <idx>
	<h>Line</h>
	<h>Slope</h>
      </idx>
      of the line through the points <m>(x_1, y_1)</m> and <m>(x_2, y_2)</m> is
      <me>\frac{y_1 - y_2}{x_1 - x_2} = \frac{y_2 - y_1}{x_2 - x_1},</me>
      provided that <m>x_1 \neq x_1</m>.
      The slope measures the rate of change in <m>y</m> with respect to <m>x</m>, as depicted in <xref ref="fig-slope"/>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The slope of a line is only defined for lines that are not vertical.
      We say the slope of a vertical line is undefined.
    </p>
  </definition>
  
  <figure xml:id="fig-slope">
    <image xml:id="img-slope">
      <latex-image>
	<xi:include parse="text" href="tex/slope.tex"/>
      </latex-image>
    </image>
    <caption>The slope of the line through the points <m>(x_1, y_1)</m> and <m>(x_2, y_2)</m>.</caption>
  </figure>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>Find the slope of the line through the points <m>(3,5)</m> and <m>(6,2)</m>.</p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
	The slope of the line through the points <m>(3,5)</m> and <m>(6,2)</m> is
	<me>\frac{2 - 5}{6 - 3} = \frac{-3}{3} = -1.</me>
	This says when the <m>x</m>-coordinate increases by 1, the <m>y</m>-coordinate decreases by 1.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
  
  <definition xml:id="def-slope_intercept">
    <title>The Slope-Intercept Form of a Line</title>
    <p>
      The <term>slope-intercept form of the line</term>
      <idx>
	<h>Line</h>
	<h>Slope-Intercept Form</h>
      </idx>
      through the point <m>(0,b)</m> with slope <m>m</m> is
      <me>y = mx + b</me>.
    </p>
  </definition>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Find <xref ref="def-slope_intercept" text="title"/> using the point <m>(0,5)</m> and slope <m>3</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
	The equation of the line through the point <m>(0,5)</m> with slope <m>3</m> is
	<me>y = 3x + 5.</me>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Find the slope and <m>y</m>-intercept for line represented by the linear equation <m>3x + 2y = 6</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
	Consider the linear equation <m>3x + 2y = 6</m>.
	This is the <xref ref="def-linear_equation" text="title"/>.
	We can place this in <xref ref="def-slope_intercept" text="title"/> by subtracting <m>3x</m> from both sides to obtain
	<me>2y = -3x + 6</me>
	then dividing both sides by <m>2</m>
	<me>y = -\frac{3}{2}x + 3.</me>
	This tells us the linear equation <m>3x + 2y = 6</m> represents the line through the point <m>(0,3)</m> with slope <m>-3/2</m>.
      </p>
      <figure>
	<image>
	  <latex-image>
	    <xi:include parse="text" href="tex/3x_2y_6.tex"/>
	  </latex-image>
	</image>
	<caption>The graph of the line <m>3x + 2y = 6</m>.</caption>
      </figure>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <definition xml:id="def-point_slope">
    <title>The Point-Slope Form of a Line</title>
    <p>
      The <term>point-slope form of the line</term>
      <idx>
	<h>Line</h>
	<h>Point-Slope Form</h>
      </idx>
      through the point <m>(x_1, y_1)</m> with slope <m>m</m> is
      <me>y - y_1 = m(x - x_1).</me>
    </p>    
  </definition>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Find the <xref ref="def-point_slope"/> using hte point <m>(1,2)</m> and the slope <m>3</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
	Using <xref ref="def-point_slope" text="title"/>, the equation of the line through <m>(1,2)</m> with slope <m>3</m> is
	<me>y - 2 = 3(x - 1).</me>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Find an equation for the line that passes through the points <m>(3,2)</m> and <m>(4,3)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
	We can use the <xref ref="def-point_slope" text="title"/> to find the line between the points <m>(3,2)</m> and <m>(4,3)</m>.
	First compute the slope of the line
	<me>m = \frac{3 - 2}{4 - 3} = \frac{1}{1} = 1.</me>
	Use either of the two points to find the equation
	<me>y - 2 = x - 3
	\quad\text{or}\quad
	y - 3 = x - 4.</me>
      </p>
      <p>
	While these equations may look different, we can compare them by placing them in <xref ref="def-slope_intercept" text="title"/>.
	For the first equation, add <m>2</m> to both sides to get
	<me>y =  x - 1</me>
	and for the second, add <m>3</m> to both sides to get
	<me>y = x - 1.</me>
	In this form, we can see that these equations represent the same line.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

